      ";s:2:"dc";a:2:{s:7:"creator";s:19:"Jess Cartner-Morley";s:4:"date";s:20:"2020-04-30T15:01:55Z";}s:7:"summary";s:884:"<p>Exclusive: application to use public money to support staff is withdrawn following criticism </p><ul><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/series/coronavirus-live/latest">Coronavirus – latest updates</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/coronavirus-outbreak">See all our coronavirus coverage</a></li></ul><p>Victoria Beckham has reversed a decision to furlough 30 staff at her fashion label and said that her team’s welfare “means everything to me” after the decision to apply for public money drew heavy criticism.</p><p>Following a change of heart by the designer and her board, the application to the government scheme has been withdrawn and all employees concerned restored to their roles.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2020/apr/30/victoria-beckham-reverses-decision-to-furlough-fashion-label-staff">Continue reading...</a>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1588258915;}i:12;a:11:{s:5:"title";s:88:"Coronavirus deaths: how does Britain compare with other countries? | David Spiegelhalter";s:4:"link";s:118:"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/coronavirus-deaths-how-does-britain-compare-with-other-countries";s:11:"description";s:1310:"<p>It’s tempting to try to construct a league table, but we’ll have to wait months, if not years, for the true picture<br></p><p><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-deaths-italy-uk-us-australia-europe-vaccine-china-global-economy-toll-latest-update-news">• Coronavirus latest updates</a></p><p><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/coronavirus-outbreak">• See all our coronavirus coverage</a></p><p>At prime minister’s questions on Wednesday, <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/29/keir-starmer-pmqs-criticises-government-over-truly-dreadful-coronavirus-death-rate">Keir Starmer</a> said he had added up a total of 27,241 coronavirus deaths so far, leaving the UK “possibly on track to have the worst death rate in Europe”.</p><p>Is he right? Unfortunately, measuring the impact of the virus is a fiendishly complex task. It’s nothing like keeping score in a game. Starmer, as a lawyer, would know that we have to define our terms carefully. And so, assuming we want to make a comparison based on death rates, we first need to decide what a death rate is.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/coronavirus-deaths-how-does-britain-compare-with-other-countries">Continue reading...</a>";s:8:"category";s:81:"Coronavirus outbreakInfectious diseasesWorld newsScienceMedical researchEpidemics";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 30 Apr 2020 13:56:56 GMT";s:4:"guid";s:118:"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/coronavirus-deaths-how-does-britain-compare-with-other-countries";s:5:"media";a:2:{s:7:"content";s:18:"
        
        ";s:14:"content_credit";s:126:"Photograph: Pippa Fowles/10 Downing Street/AFP via Getty ImagesPhotograph: Pippa Fowles/10 Downing Street/AFP via Getty Images";}s:7:"content";s:14:"
      
      ";s:2:"dc";a:2:{s:7:"creator";s:19:"David Spiegelhalter";s:4:"date";s:20:"2020-04-30T13:56:56Z";}s:7:"summary";s:1310:"<p>It’s tempting to try to construct a league table, but we’ll have to wait months, if not years, for the true picture<br></p><p><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-deaths-italy-uk-us-australia-europe-vaccine-china-global-economy-toll-latest-update-news">• Coronavirus latest updates</a></p><p><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/coronavirus-outbreak">• See all our coronavirus coverage</a></p><p>At prime minister’s questions on Wednesday, <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/29/keir-starmer-pmqs-criticises-government-over-truly-dreadful-coronavirus-death-rate">Keir Starmer</a> said he had added up a total of 27,241 coronavirus deaths so far, leaving the UK “possibly on track to have the worst death rate in Europe”.</p><p>Is he right? Unfortunately, measuring the impact of the virus is a fiendishly complex task. It’s nothing like keeping score in a game. Starmer, as a lawyer, would know that we have to define our terms carefully. And so, assuming we want to make a comparison based on death rates, we first need to decide what a death rate is.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/coronavirus-deaths-how-does-britain-compare-with-other-countries">Continue reading...</a>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1588255016;}i:13;a:11:{s:5:"title";s:79:"Lockdown should be easy for me, so why is it like doing time? | Ottessa Mosfegh";s:4:"link";s:121:"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/lockdown-novel-self-isolation-coronavirus-pandemic-ottessa-moshfegh";s:11:"description";s:1848:"<p>I wrote a novel about self-isolation, yet I’m struggling with the profound loss of agency the coronavirus pandemic has caused<br><br></p><ul><li>Ottessa Moshfegh is the author of My Year of Rest and Relaxation</li><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/14/coronavirus-live-updates-uk-us-australia-italy-europe-school-shutdown-sport-events-cancelled-latest-update-news">Coronavirus – latest updates</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/coronavirus-outbreak">See all our coronavirus coverage</a></li></ul><p>In 2018 I published a <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/jul/11/my-year-rest-relaxation-ottessa-moshfegh-review">novel</a> about a young woman in New York City who doesn’t leave her apartment. It was an interesting premise to me at the time, Manhattan being a place where daily living has much to do with going out and mixing with people, witnessing and being witnessed, taking part in the collective excitement of being alive.</p><p>I wondered just how jaded, depressed, antisocial, irreverent and irritable one must be to want to hide from life to such an extreme. I figured this character must be suffering deeply, so I built her backstory to include a cold, drunk, critical mother and a sterile, unfeeling father. And then I killed them, just to make my protagonist even worse off. She doesn’t want to feel the resulting grief of being orphaned in her 20s, so she tries to bypass it by sleeping. She theorises that if she spends long enough asleep, her cells will regenerate the number of times necessary for them to forget the memory of trauma they’ve stored inside. If grief were an illness, sleep is the cure.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/lockdown-novel-self-isolation-coronavirus-pandemic-ottessa-moshfegh">Continue reading...</a>";s:8:"category";s:66:"Coronavirus outbreakBooksOttessa MoshfeghSocietyWorld newsNew York";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 30 Apr 2020 11:51:11 GMT";s:4:"guid";s:121:"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/lockdown-novel-self-isolation-coronavirus-pandemic-ottessa-moshfegh";s:5:"media";a:2:{s:7:"content";s:18:"
        
        ";s:14:"content_credit";s:74:"Illustration: Nate Kitch/The GuardianIllustration: Nate Kitch/The Guardian";}s:7:"content";s:14:"
      
      ";s:2:"dc";a:2:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Ottessa Moshfegh";s:4:"date";s:20:"2020-04-30T11:51:11Z";}s:7:"summary";s:1848:"<p>I wrote a novel about self-isolation, yet I’m struggling with the profound loss of agency the coronavirus pandemic has caused<br><br></p><ul><li>Ottessa Moshfegh is the author of My Year of Rest and Relaxation</li><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/14/coronavirus-live-updates-uk-us-australia-italy-europe-school-shutdown-sport-events-cancelled-latest-update-news">Coronavirus – latest updates</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/coronavirus-outbreak">See all our coronavirus coverage</a></li></ul><p>In 2018 I published a <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/jul/11/my-year-rest-relaxation-ottessa-moshfegh-review">novel</a> about a young woman in New York City who doesn’t leave her apartment. It was an interesting premise to me at the time, Manhattan being a place where daily living has much to do with going out and mixing with people, witnessing and being witnessed, taking part in the collective excitement of being alive.</p><p>I wondered just how jaded, depressed, antisocial, irreverent and irritable one must be to want to hide from life to such an extreme. I figured this character must be suffering deeply, so I built her backstory to include a cold, drunk, critical mother and a sterile, unfeeling father. And then I killed them, just to make my protagonist even worse off. She doesn’t want to feel the resulting grief of being orphaned in her 20s, so she tries to bypass it by sleeping. She theorises that if she spends long enough asleep, her cells will regenerate the number of times necessary for them to forget the memory of trauma they’ve stored inside. If grief were an illness, sleep is the cure.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/lockdown-novel-self-isolation-coronavirus-pandemic-ottessa-moshfegh">Continue reading...</a>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1588247471;}i:14;a:11:{s:5:"title";s:105:"After the restlessness finally there's stillness: my last stage of coronavirus isolation | Brigid Delaney";s:4:"link";s:140:"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/may/01/after-the-restlessness-finally-theres-stillness-my-last-stage-of-coronavirus-isolation";s:11:"description";s:640:"<p>I’ve been to monasteries and religious retreats seeking calmness. The pandemic is giving me the same experience at home </p><p>As the Covid-19 shutdown endures in various forms, some people may find they’re settling into a slower-paced rhythm. There’s nowhere to go, nowhere to be. We might be in this liminal space for a while.</p><p>At times this stagnation fills me with horror, but I’m also trying to see the stay-at-home order as an opportunity.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/may/01/after-the-restlessness-finally-theres-stillness-my-last-stage-of-coronavirus-isolation">Continue reading...</a>";s:8:"category";s:108:"Coronavirus outbreakMeditationReligionHealth & wellbeingLife and styleAustralia newsLeonard CohenFranz Kafka";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 30 Apr 2020 17:30:02 GMT";s:4:"guid";s:140:"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/may/01/after-the-restlessness-finally-theres-stillness-my-last-stage-of-coronavirus-isolation";s:5:"media";a:2:{s:7:"content";s:18:"
        
