massive blocks of cheddar and endless bowls of jelly<br></p><p>Many years before his death, I remember the writer John Bayley saying that while grieving the loss of his wife, Iris Murdoch, he spent a lot of time, in his head, in his childhood. It was clearly a pain reflex, a way of escaping the present into his most vivid memories and a sense of making time elastic. Trapped inside, going nuts, there aren’t too many ways to get away at present, but revisiting long-distant comforts is one.</p><p>The quickest way to do this is through food. Incidental data in the United States suggests that for the past two months, among the overall boom in grocery sales has been a spike in the consumption of comfort food. Sales of chocolate, ice-cream and popcorn are up, as well as expensive processed foods that, before the lockdown, might have been considered an unhealthy extravagance.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/crisis-binge-comfort-food--coronavirus">Continue reading...</a>";s:8:"category";s:60:"Coronavirus outbreakInfectious diseasesFoodUS newsWorld news";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 30 Apr 2020 16:27:29 GMT";s:4:"guid";s:92:"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/30/crisis-binge-comfort-food--coronavirus";s:5:"media";a:2:{s:7:"content";s:18:"
        
