      ";s:2:"dc";a:2:{s:7:"creator";s:41:"David Conn and Philip Oltermann in Berlin";s:4:"date";s:20:"2020-04-30T16:25:50Z";}s:7:"summary";s:949:"<ul><li>Swiss attorney general at odds with Fifa</li><li>Police reports allege gifts made in return for votes</li></ul><p>Fifa is preparing to press the authorities in Switzerland to prosecute Sepp Blatter for alleged corruption, after the Swiss attorney general dropped part of its investigation despite police reports listing years of apparent gifts and payments provided to the then <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/sep/29/jack-warner-banned-football-life-fifa-ethics-committee">vice-president, Jack Warner</a>, in return for votes for Blatter in Fifa presidential elections. </p><p>Senior Fifa officials are understood to be considering all options if the case against Blatter is discontinued, potentially including suing the attorney general’s office for failing to prosecute.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/30/fifa-action-after-swiss-drop-part-sepp-blatter-investigation">Continue reading...</a>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1588263950;}i:52;a:11:{s:5:"title";s:71:"La Liga to start testing players on Monday after government green light";s:4:"link";s:97:"https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/30/la-liga-start-testing-players-monday-coronavirus";s:11:"description";s:713:"<ul><li>League aims to resume matches in mid-June</li><li>Resumption dependent on approval from ministry of health</li></ul><p>The Spanish government has approved a protocol for sporting activity, paving the way for La Liga clubs to begin testing players for Covid-19 on Monday with a view to returning to training the following week. </p><p>The league is optimistic that this step will allow it to restart the competition in mid-June, although all decisions still depend on approval from the ministry of health and on the numbers infected by coronavirus continuing to decline.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/footba