      ";s:2:"dc";a:2:{s:7:"creator";s:10:"Ben Fisher";s:4:"date";s:20:"2020-04-30T17:23:23Z";}s:7:"summary";s:1272:"<ul><li>Project Restart protocols also suggest disinfecting corner flags</li><li>Brighton striker against playing matches at neutral venues</li></ul><p>Glenn Murray has described the Premier League’s proposal for players to cover their faces by wearing snoods or masks during training as “farcical” and has questioned whether players should adopt such measures as the top flight targets a return to group sessions. A seven-page document details the suggested protocols, which are part of Project Restart, the league’s plan to resume the interrupted season, and will be discussed by club executives during a <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/30/premier-league-clubs-meet-medicine-v-money-top-agenda">conference call on Friday</a>.</p><p>The Brighton striker questioned whether the protocols, which range from cones and corner flags being disinfected before and after use by staff wearing personal protective equipment (PPE) to cars being parked three spaces apart, were sensible or realistic. Players would also have to pass a Covid-19 antigen test in the 48 hours before group training.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/30/glenn-murray-condemns-premier-league-face-mask-guidelines-as-farcical">Continue reading...</a>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1588267403;}i:57;a:11:{s:5:"title";s:57:"Coronavirus: scientists caution against reopening schools";s:4:"link";s:102:"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/30/coronavirus-scientists-caution-against-reopening-schools";s:11:"description";s:1127:"<p>Study finds children may be as infectious as adults – but Unicef warns closures put vulnerable pupils at risk</p><ul><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/series/coronavirus-live/latest">Coronavirus – latest updates</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/coronavirus-outbreak">See all our coronavirus coverage</a></li></ul><p>Scientists have cautioned against the reopening of schools after findings suggested children could be as infectious as adults.</p><p>The study, which was carried out by the team of leading German virologist <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/26/virologist-christian-drosten-germany-coronavirus-expert-interview">Christian Drosten</a>, found that even though children tended to have far milder symptoms, those infected appeared to have the same levels of circulating virus in their body as adults. This suggests schools and nurseries could act as hubs of Covid-19 transmission if current restrictions are lifted.</p> <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/30/coronavirus-scientists-caution-against-reopening-schools">Continue reading...</a>";s:8:"category";s:50:"Coronavirus outbreakSchoolsUK newsEducationGermany";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 30 Apr 2020 15:45:14 GMT";s:4:"guid";s:102:"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/30/coronavirus-scientists-caution-against-reopening-schools";s:5:"media";a:2:{s:7:"content";s:18:"
        
